#calculatint the within sum of squares
#Method 1
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
wss =[] 
for i in range(2,11):
    KM = KMeans(n_clusters=i)
    KM.fit(newcars_df)
    wss.append(KM.inertia_)
wss

#passing cluster range 2 to 10 clusters
#method 2
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import sklearn.metrics

cluster_range= range (2,11)
cluster_errors= []

for num_clusters in cluster_range:
    clusters = KMeans(num_clusters,n_init=5)
    clusters.fit(newcars_df)
    #attributes
    labels = clusters.labels_
    centroid= clusters.cluster_centers_
    cluster_errors.append(clusters.inertia_)

In [58]:
## 3D plots of clusters
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = Axes3D(fig, rect=[0, 0, .95, 1], elev=20, azim=60)
k_means.fit(newcars_df)
labels = k_means.labels_
ax.scatter(newcars_df.iloc[:, 0], newcars_df.iloc[:, 1], newcars_df.iloc[:, 4],c=labels.astype(np.float), edgecolor='k')
ax.w_xaxis.set_ticklabels([])
ax.w_yaxis.set_ticklabels([])
ax.w_zaxis.set_ticklabels([])
ax.set_xlabel('Casing')
ax.set_ylabel('c_temp')
ax.set_zlabel('Bearingt')
ax.set_title('3D plot of KMeans Clustering')
